<section xml:id="list-algorithms-iterators_getting-iterators"
         xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

  <title>Getting Iterators</title>

  <p>
    An iterator only makes sense in the context of a specific collection. We can't just make a <pf>ListIterator</pf> out of thin air - we need to get it from a list. The list class will construct the iterator for us, initializing it with the right pointer, and then give it to us.</p>

    <p>
    Say we wanted to add an iterator to our <pf>SinglyLinkedList</pf> class. We would could add two functions like this:
  </p>
  
  <listing>
    <program>
      <![CDATA[ 
    template<typename T>
    class SinglyLinkedList {
    ...
    public:
      ListIterator<T> begin() {
          // Return an iterator pointing to the first node
          return ListIterator<T>(head);
      }

      ListIterator<T> end() {
          // Return an iterator representing "one past the end"
          return ListIterator<T>(nullptr);
      }
      ...
    };
      ]]>
    </program>
  </listing>

  <p>
    The <pf>.begin()</pf> function is supposed to return an iterator that points to the first element in the list. It does this by constructing a <pf>ListIterator</pf> initialized with the <pf>head</pf> pointer of the list. The <pf>.end()</pf> function returns an iterator that represents the position just past the last element in the list. In our implementation, if you have a pointer that is at the last node, and then advance it to the <pf>next</pf> address, it will become <pf>nullptr</pf>. So we can represent the "one past the end" position with an iterator initialized with <pf>nullptr</pf>.
  </p>

  <insight>
    <p>An end iterator is always represents the location you end up at if you go <q>one step too far</q> while iterating through a collection.</p>
  </insight>

  <p>
    Now, our loop to print out all the elements in the list is complete. <pf>myList.begin()</pf> gives us an iterator that holds a pointer to the head node. We will keep advancing that iterator until it reports that it is equal to <pf>myList.end()</pf>, which is the iterator holding <pf>nullptr</pf>. 
  </p>

  <program>
    <![CDATA[
    for(ListIterator<int> it = myList.begin(); it != myList.end(); ++it) {
        cout << *it << " ";
    }
    ]]>
  </program>

</section>